\begin_layout Chapter
Simulation Studies
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:5"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter, we study the methods proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "part:2"

\end_inset

 in a simulation environment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we formally demonstrate that the exact generalized bridge sampler
 proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:4"

\end_inset

 produces samples from the desired target distribution, and is empirically
 robust to the relaxation of certain assumptions made in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:2"

\end_inset

.
 We also confirm that the approximate sampler does not draw from the true
 generalized bridge distribution, but note qualitatively that the approximate
 sample paths are still of high quality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, we show that the MCEM scheme proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:EM"

\end_inset

 converges to the set of Kullback-Liebler divergence minimizing parameters
 in a variety of scenarios, often very quickly.
 Furthermore, we demonstrate that the approximate generalized bridge sampler
 provides samples of a sufficiently high quality that MCEM estimation is
 not adversely affected.
 Given that the approximate sampler is one to two orders of magnitude faster
 than the exact sampler, this is a welcome finding and lends the proposed
 MCEM scheme increased utility in inference applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Objects and Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As usual, we begin by fixing the objects of study.
 We will focus in this chapter on Lévy processes of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dX_{t}=-\lambda\left(X_{t}-\mu\right)dt+\sigma dL_{t},\label{eq:ou-sde}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some initial condition on 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

 and a Lévy process 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 Solutions to this SDE are known as Lévy-driven Ornstein-Uhlenbeck (OU)
 processes.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a Wiener process, 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is an Itô diffusion satisfying the assumptions outlined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "chap:2"

\end_inset

; this so-called Gaussian OU process is both theoretically interesting (represen
ting the only non-trivial stationary, Gaussian, and Markovian process) and
 practically useful (used to model everything from springs to currency exchange
 rates—see standard physics references or 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hirsa-2012"

\end_inset

 for applications in finance).
 In general, we will refer to the parameter vector of such a process as
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=(\mu,\lambda,\sigma)$
\end_inset

, and the joint law at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 of a solution to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ou-sde"

\end_inset

 with initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}\sim F$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\theta}(F,L)$
\end_inset

.
 We fix 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{*}=(0,1,1)$
\end_inset

 as the parameter vector of interest unless otherwise specified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all simulations to be carried out, the relevant process is simulated
 over the time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 with a step size 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=1/100$
\end_inset

 using the Euler scheme (for OU processes, this is equivalent to the Milstein
 scheme).
 In the following sections, we will repeatedly need to sample from 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\theta}(F,L)$
\end_inset

; this can be easily done by simulating an unconstrained solution to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ou-sde"

\end_inset

 with initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}\sim F$
\end_inset

, and taking its values at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

.
 The exact generalized bridge sampler uses 
\begin_inset Formula $M=10$
\end_inset

 (the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

-values simulated in order to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}$
\end_inset

) and no burn-in since its proposals are independent of one another, and
 all optimizations are carried out using the DEoptim (differential evolution
 optimization) package in R on default settings.
 The computations in this paper were run on the Odyssey cluster supported
 by the Research Computing Group in the FAS Division of Science at Harvard
 University, and the Research Computing Environment supported by the Institute
 for Quantitative Social Science at Harvard University.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sampling 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

-Bridges
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we will test whether the generalized bridge samplers proposed
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:4"

\end_inset

 indeed draw from the true generalized bridge distribution.
 Note that an unconstrained solution to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ou-sde"

\end_inset

 with initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}\sim F$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as a generalized bridge with endpoints equal in distribution
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\theta}(F,L)$
\end_inset

; as usual, we will call such a bridge a 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\theta}(F,L)$
\end_inset

-bridge of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 This insight suggests that we merely need to verify that a 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\theta}(F,L)$
\end_inset

-bridge of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is equal in distribution to the appropriate unconstrained process.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:KS-stats"

\end_inset

, we present Kolmogorov-Smirnov statistics comparing the marginal distribution
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1/2$
\end_inset

 of unconstrained processes to their 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\theta}(F,L)$
\end_inset

-bridges of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 sampled approximately and exactly, as well as the relative running times
 of the two samplers.
 In addition to a Gaussian OU process, which satisfies the assumptions of
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "chap:2"

\end_inset

, we also test the generalized bridge samplers for an OU process driven
 by a standard 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

-stable Lévy process 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, which is not an Itô diffusion (in fact, every increment of this process
 has infinite variance), and the Wiener process, which does not have finite
 speed measure.
 Note that the Wiener process is a Gaussian OU diffusion with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=(0,0,1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

