MCEM iterations for inference on the parameters of a Gaussian OU process,
 given that its endpoints are distributed 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\theta^{*}}(\mathcal{N}(0,1/2),W)$
\end_inset

, using approximate and exact generalized bridge samplers.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th iteration uses 
\begin_inset Formula $100\times\left\lfloor i^{1.2}\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

 MC samples.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that MCEM scheme using either the exact or approximate sampler effective
ly converges after two iterations.
 As is usual for MCEM schemes, the algorithm produces parameter estimates
 sampled from some neighborhood of the true parameter value, instead of
 converging deterministically to such a value.
 The slightly thinner tails of the sample paths drawn from the approximate
 sampler near 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1/2$
\end_inset

, at least in this case, do not seem to have a significant adverse impact
 on the quality of the Monte Carlo estimates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:diff-diffusions"

\end_inset

, we present a comprehensive evaluation of the ability of the proposed MCEM
 scheme to estimate the parameter vector for a Gaussian OU diffusion given
 that the diffusion's endpoints follow a variety of given joint distributions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular, we consider joint distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\theta^{*}}(F,W)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $F\sim\mathcal{N}(0,1/2)$
\end_inset

, as well 
\begin_inset Formula $F\sim\hat{\mathcal{N}}(0,1/2)$
\end_inset

—a discrete distribution consisting of 
\begin_inset Formula $100$
\end_inset

 fixed samples from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}(0,1/2)$
\end_inset

—and 
\begin_inset Formula $F\sim2\mbox{Bern}-1$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $L=W$
\end_inset

, as well as the cases when 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a standard variance gamma process and a standard normal inverse Gaussian
 process.
 In these non-Gaussian cases, the resulting joint distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\theta^{*}}(F,L)$
\end_inset

 is not a member of the family of joint distributions that can induced by
 a Gaussian OU process, and thus the MCEM algorithm will perform maximum
 likelihood estimation under model misspecification.
 However, since the form of the drift and diffusion coefficients remains
 the same, and both the variance gamma and normal inverse Gaussian distributions
 have finite variance, we expect that the resulting parameter estimates
 ought to be consistent for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{*}$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:diff-diffusions"

\end_inset

 confirms that this is indeed the case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, we can see from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:diff-diffusions"

\end_inset

 that the approximate and exact samplers are effectively indistinguishable
 in the quality of their parameter estimates after 10 MCEM iterations; the
 only major difference between using the two samplers is that the MCEM scheme
 using the exact sampler is prohibitively slow.
 In fact, the computational time used by exact sampling is on the order
 of two magnitudes longer than the time used by approximate sampling.
 We conjecture that for all but the most extreme of distributional data
 (i.e.
 conditioning a process which mean reverts to zero on an endpoint joint
 distribution with marginal distributions centered far from zero), an MCEM
 scheme relying on approximate generalized bridge sampling will provide
 parameter estimates of sufficiently high quality, especially given the
 inherent variance of MCEM estimates in the first place.
\end_layout

